entury origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":40,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Rose Seahorse was born in 1415, in England. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Richard Heathcote."},"et":{"1415–":"1415–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1440–1492":"1440–1492","1415–Female":"1415–Surnud","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","Abt 1430":"umbes 1430","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1492":"1492","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1415–":"1415–Kuollut","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1440–1492":"1440–1492","1415–Female":"1415–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","Abt 1430":"noin 1430","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1492":"1492","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"E